03 Prove - Assignment¶

Objectives¶

  • Using OpenCV to work with images

Instructions¶

  1. Go to the GitHub folder for week03/assignment and download all of the files found in this folder to a location on your computer.
  2. The file project.py
  • There are a number of filters that can be used on images.
  • Introduction to using kernels in filtering.
  • You will be implimenting a general function that can apply different filters.

Files for this project

  1. project.py - Your project code.
  2. testfunctions.py - Code file that is used to test your code. Do not modify or submit this file.
  3. src-image1.jpg - Image file for your project and testing.
  4. src-image2.jpg - Image file for your project and testing.

Functions you need to impliment¶

1) convert_image(srcfilename, dstfilename)¶

Purpose:

This function will open the image given by the argument srcfilename, convert it and save it to the given dstfilename file.

Arguments:

  • srcfilename: source file name of the image to convert
  • dstfilename: file name of the image to save the converted image

2) resize_image(srcfilename, dstfilename, scale)¶

Purpose:

This function will open the image given by the argument srcfilename, resize the image to the given scale. Then save the resulting scaled image to dstfilename

Arguments:

  • srcfilename: source file name of the image to convert
  • dstfilename: file name of the image to save the converted image
  • scale: scale factor as an integer

3) border_image(srcfilename, dstfilename, width, color)¶

Purpose:

This function will open the image given by the argument srcfilename, enlarge it to handle the border, color the new border and save it to the given dstfilename file.

Arguments:

  • srcfilename: source file name of the image to convert
  • dstfilename: file name of the image to save the converted image
  • width: Width of the border
  • color: Color of the border as a tuple

4) create_mondrian()¶

Purpose:

This is the "Make it your own" challenge. You are to create a Mondrian "painting". You must have at least 5 squares in your final image. You will be graded on how close you can get to the style of what Mondrian created. Your image must be of your own creation - don't copy another Mondrian painting.

This function will display your completed image to the screen.

Piet Mondrian – 'Abstract Painting as We Know It' | TateShots
